mediaNotes: Pair of worm-eating warblers calling.

I first encountered this WEWA singing in a gully choked with rhodo.  He flew briefly up to a short locust on a bend in the forest service road.  In the first two parts of this recording, he has flown up into a half dead oak (approx. 15 meters up) that was growing on a dry hillside whose understory was blooming mountain laurel and white pine saplings.  In the second part of the recording, he has flown back down to the small locust sapling where he is joined by two CACH.
